<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Construction Spending: Spending for new construction dipped in June but showed 
signs of stabilizing after a volatile first half, according to a study by F. W. 
Dodge, a financial information division of McGraw-Hill. 
</P>
<P>
Dodge said its index of new construction contracts fell in June to 153 from 156 
in May. Spending for new construction totaled $240.72 billion in June, compared 
to May's $245.71 billion. Despite the overall decline, Dodge found evidence 
that construction spending was leveling off after having fallen to a four-year 
low in April as builders found financing harder to come by. 
</P>
</TEXT>
