<P>
BAKER AILING, TAKES DAY OFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SINGAPORE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secretary of State James A. Baker III was forced to cancel several meetings 
here Monday and rest in bed after he suddenly became ill, State Department 
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said. 
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state departed from a conference of the Asia-Pacific Economic 
Cooperation forum to return to his quarters, leaving it to Commerce Secretary 
Robert A. Mosbacher to give a speech that Baker was scheduled to deliver. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not something serious. He just doesn't feel well, and he's resting today. 
It's nothing to be alarmed about," Tutwiler said. She said Baker had developed 
a fever by the time he woke up Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Tutwiler said that Baker does not plan to alter the itinerary for the remainder 
of his 10-day visit to Asia. 
</P>
