<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGIONAL ROUNDUP: POLLUTION RESEARCH &amp; CONTROL MAY BE SOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pollution Research &amp; Control Corp., a Glendale company that makes 
air-quality monitoring devices, said it is considering offers to buy the 
company. The company declined to name any of the potential buyers, but said it 
had "entered into preliminary discussions" with them. 
</P>
<P>
Pollution Research also announced that it would report that sales of its 
primary product, devices for measuring ambient air pollution, would show a 
"significant decline" in the fourth quarter that ended June 30. Pollution 
Research attributed the drop in sales to lower than expected demand for the 
devices in the United States and Korea. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, Pollution Research said that as a cost-cutting measure, it will 
sell 75% of its Air Instruments &amp; Measurement subsidiary to its management 
in exchange for royalties from the unit's sales. Albert E. Gosselin Jr., chief 
executive officer of Pollution Research, said AIM's management in turn would 
probably sell the unit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
