<SECTION>
<P>
World Report; Part H; Page 1; Column 1; Foreign Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
117 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: CAIRO; 
</P>
<P>
IRANIANS ARE BACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iran takes another step toward patching up its relations with the Arab world 
when it participates for the first time in several years in this week's annual 
meeting of foreign ministers of the Organization of the Islamic Conference in 
Cairo. 
</P>
<P>
Iran's isolation from its fellow Muslims in the Arab world was exacerbated by 
its long and bloody war with Iraq, but in another gesture earlier this month 
Tehran sent its foreign minister to Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
Among other issues, the 46 Islamic members are expected during their five-day 
meeting to criticize Saudi Arabia's handling of pilgrimages to Mecca and to 
plot strategy for defending the controversial "Zionism is racism" resolution in 
the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
