<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
WATCH IS KEPT ON SAGGING SIDEWALK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When she first got the call that a sidewalk was moving at a downtown park, 
Deputy City Clerk Roe Allen said that she didn't know what to think. But the 
unidentified woman was adamant. 
</P>
<P>
"She said she wanted to report the sidewalk was moving at Heisler Park near the 
bowling green and that we better get somebody out there right away to look at 
it," Allen said. The Friday caller insisted that she could actually see the 
pathway shift. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't take it too seriously because we get a lot of crazy calls here," 
Allen said, "but I did follow through." 
</P>
<P>
The call was no hoax, city workers discovered when they arrived at the site 
about 4:30 p.m. About 20 feet of walkway near Jasmine Street and Cliff Drive 
had simply slid 2 to 3 feet into the cliff above the ocean. After checking with 
Caltech in Pasadena on Monday, Municipal Services Director Terry Brandt ruled 
out the possibility that the landslide was caused by seismic activity. The 
cause, he concluded, was recent high tides and high surf. 
</P>
<P>
The area where the approximately 8-foot-wide walkway collapsed is the scene of 
previous erosion, he said. About five years ago, a tree in the vicinity was 
uprooted by erosion, Brandt said. 
</P>
<P>
The area has been cordoned off and is being watched around the clock by beach 
patrol and police officers. Geologists will determine what can be done to 
repair the damage. 
</P>
<P>
Debbie Litwin, the first beach patrol officer on the site when the landslide 
was reported, said the slide started with a slight fracture in the earth. 
</P>
<P>
"It started out a really small crack and just started getting bigger,' she 
said. 'It . . . very gradually fell." LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, (A2) Laguna on the Move: About 20 feet of walkway near Jasmine Street 
and Cliff Drive in Laguna Beach slid two to three feet down the cliff above the 
ocean. The city has ruled out the possibility that the landslide was caused by 
seismic activity. Officials believe the cause is recent high tides and high 
surf. Above, the shift is visible at left. JOHN FUNG / Los Angeles Times; 
Photo, Laguna officials are watching this walkway in Heisler Park, where about 
20 feet of sidewalk has slid down the bluff. JOHN FUNG / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
