<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY; 
</P>
<P>
BERNARDI LEADS BID TO OVERTURN CITY'S CAMPAIGN FINANCING PLAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City Councilman Ernani Bernardi and state Sen. Quentin L. Kopp today announced 
a legal challenge to the city's voter-approved plans to provide partial public 
financing for municipal campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
Kopp (I-San Francisco) was one of the authors of state Proposition 73, enacted 
by the voters in 1988, which bans public campaign financing. 
</P>
<P>
He and Bernardi are going to court to halt implementation of the public 
campaign financing provisions of City Charter Amendment H, a comprehensive 
ethics measure approved by Los Angeles voters in June. 
</P>
<P>
Amendment H requires the council to place $2 million each year into a trust for 
matching campaign funds to be handed out to qualifying candidates in the 1993 
election and beyond. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
