<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRITISH BAND TO BE DEPORTED AFTER ARREST ON POT CHARGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
VICTORIA, Seychelles 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Five musicians and two technicians from the British pop band UB40, arrested on 
suspicion of possessing marijuana, will be deported from the Seychelles, police 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Commissioner Raymond Louise told reporters there was enough 
evidence to charge the seven, but authorities had decided to deport them from 
the islands in the Indian Ocean instead. 
</P>
<P>
Conviction for possession of illegal drugs in the Seychelles carries a 
mandatory three-year jail sentence. 
</P>
<P>
Louise did not say when group members, who were taken into custody Monday after 
police raided their hotel room, would have to leave. 
</P>
<P>
UB40 gave a concert Saturday and their performance was described by the 
islands' only newspaper, the Seychelles Nation, as a technical fiasco. An 
organizer said a bottle of water accidentally fell in the music-mixing 
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
